  "title": "Abdominal wall",
  "body_html": "<b>Overview of the abdominal muscles</b><br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb349b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb349.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>Image sourced from </span><a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdominal external oblique muscle'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >Wikipedia</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb349b.png'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER><br /><i>Diagram illustrating cross sectional anatomy of the abdominal wall</i><br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti031b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti031.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><br /><b>Extent of the anterior abdominal muscles</b><br /><br /><div class=\"table-responsive\"><table class = \"tlarge table table-striped table-bordered\"  data-role=\"table\" id=\"tableid1\" ><thead><tr><th>Muscle</th><th>Origin</th><th>Insertion</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>External oblique</td><td>Lower 8 ribs (7-12)</td><td>Xiphoid process<br />Linea alba<br />Pubic crest<br />Pubic tubercle<br />Iliac crest</td></tr><tr><td>Internal oblique</td><td>Lumbar fascia<br />Iliac crest<br />Lateral 2/3 inguinal ligament</td><td>Lower 3 ribs (10-12) and costal cartilages<br />Xiphoid process<br />Linea alba<br />Pubic symphysis</td></tr><tr><td>Transversus abdominus</td><td>Lower 6 costal cartilages<br />Lumbar fascia<br />Iliac crest<br />Lateral 1/3 inguinal ligament</td><td>Xiphoid process<br />Linea alba<br />Pubic symphysis</td></tr><tr><td>Rectus abdominus</td><td>Pubic Symphysis<br />Pubic crest</td><td>5th-7th costal cartilages<br />Xiphoid process</td></tr></tbody></table></div><br /><b>Nerve supply of anterior abdominal muscles</b><br /><br /><div class=\"table-responsive\"><table class = \"tlarge table table-striped table-bordered\"  data-role=\"table\" id=\"tableid2\" ><thead><tr><th>Muscle</th><th>Nerve Supply</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>External Oblique</td><td>Thoracoabdominal nerves (T7-11)<br />Subcostal nerve (T12)</td></tr><tr><td>Internal Oblique</td><td>Thoracoabdominal nerve (T6-T11)<br />Subcostal nerve (T12)<br />Iliohypogastric nerve (L1)<br />Ilioinguinal nerve (L1)</td></tr><tr><td>Transversus abdominus</td><td>Thoracoabdominal nerve (T6-T11)<br />Subcostal nerve (T12)<br />Iliohypogastric nerve (L1)<br />Ilioinguinal nerve (L1)</td></tr><tr><td>Rectus abdominus</td><td>Segmentally by thoracoabdominal nerves (T7 to T11)</td></tr></tbody></table></div><br /><b>Arrangement of the abdominal obliques</b><br /><br /><i>Diagram illustrating external oblique lateral view</i><br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb105b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb105.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>Image sourced from </span><a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdominal external oblique muscle'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >Wikipedia</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb105b.png'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER><br /><i>Diagram illustrating internal & external oblique</i><br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb104b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb104.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>Image sourced from </span><a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdominal external oblique muscle'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >Wikipedia</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/swb104b.png'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>On the left side the external oblique has been removed to reveal the internal oblique below</div><br /><i>Diagram illustrating transversus abdominus anterior and lateral views</i><br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti204b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti204.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti203b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/fti203.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><br /><i>Diagram illustrating rectus abdominus</i><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left